utc": "04:30", "currency": "GBP", "title": "HPI y/y", "impact": "Low"}], "editorial": "Cable sits at 1.3383 heading into the London afternoon, having spent the best part of the past fortnight unwinding a sharp rally that carried the pair to a multi-week high of 1.3558 on 15 July. That spike now looks increasingly like an exhaustion move \u2014 the daily chart shows a clear sequence of lower closes in the sessions that followed, with yesterday's candle printing a modest range between 1.3360 and 1.3456 before settling near the lows. The desk's bias is neutral, and the price action since mid-July does little to argue otherwise.\n\nThe structure story is one of a pair that ran hard into overhead supply and has since been digesting the move lower. The prior reaction zone around 1.3483 capped multiple intraday attempts last week, and the more significant cluster near 1.3483\u20131.3556 has now acted as a ceiling across six distinct touches. Below current price, the structure support at 1.3371 has so far held on two tests \u2014 the 23 July low of 1.3360 probed beneath it briefly before recovering, which is worth watching. A clean daily close beneath that zone would shift the short-term picture meaningfully. Deeper support from a prior reaction zone sits well below at 1.3141, though that remains a secondary consideration unless the current range breaks down materially.\n\nOn the hourly chart, the picture is one of compression. After the sharp sell-off through the late evening of 21 July \u2014 which saw price drop from 1.3456 to a low of 1.3360 in roughly nine hours \u2014 the H1 bars have been remarkably contained. Since the early hours of 22 July, the pair has oscillated in a roughly 20-pip band either side of 1.3380, with no meaningful directional conviction. Volume-driven moves have been absent and the candles are small-bodied throughout the morning session, suggesting the market is in a holding pattern ahead of a catalyst.\n\nThat catalyst may already have passed. UK CPI data landed at 02:00 UTC this morning \u2014 the highest-impact event on today's calendar \u2014 and the muted price response visible on the H1 chart implies the print was broadly in line with expectations, or at least not sufficiently surprising to shift the narrative around Bank of England policy. The accompanying PPI and RPI releases, along with the HPI figure at 04:30, carry lower market impact and are unlikely to generate fresh momentum independently.\n\nWhat would change the read? A sustained hourly close back above 1.3452 would suggest the corrective phase is stalling and bring the 1.3483 prior reaction zone back into focus. Conversely, a confirmed daily close beneath the 1.3371 structure support would open the door to a more extended pullback scenario, with the 1.3290\u20131.3300 area the next region of note. Until either of those scenarios materialises, the range-bound read holds.\n\nThis is editorial analysis, not financial advice. Trading involves substantial risk of loss.", "sample": false}